\s+2What you should know before starting the installation\s-2

Installing the universal character generator requires that you disassemble your computer.
When you do this, the "warranty seal" will be broken.  The strictest reading
of the Radio Shack repair policy is that any remaining warranty (original
or a repair warranty) will be void if the seal is broken, and if the machine
is ever repaired again by Radio Shack, the technicians may remove or replace
any "alien" components to restore the unit to its original state.

However, in 1982 Ed Juge (the Press Officer of Radio Shack/Tandy)
clarified how "alien" modifications are handled by
Radio Shack Service Centers.  In "TRS-80 Microcomputer News", July/August
1982, and in "80-US", May 1982, Mr. Juge states that Radio Shack will
service a machine with a modification and will ignore it if doesn't seem
to be hurting anything.  If the modification prevents the technician
from properly testing the unit, they may ask you for permission to remove
it. 

It is also possible
that some future repair may require the CPU board be exchanged and the
technician may not notice that you have a different character
generator in your
machine and may fail to move it to the replacement
board.  To avoid this, be sure to tell the technician that you have the
new character generator installed.  Be sure this
gets written down on the repair ticket in case a different person ends up
working on your machine. 


\s+2Installation\s-2

As discussed above, installing the character generator requires your computer
to be disassembled.  The entire job can be done in about 30 minutes.  Two
steps are much easier if you have a second person to help.  Read through the
following steps and if the procedure seems beyond your capabilities, seek
help from a local computer shop, TV repair store or local college.

The installation instructions are written for the person who has never
disassembled a Model 4P before, but is able to perform repairs
on the car or the toaster.   If you have installed a battery-powered
clock in your computer or changed a disk drive, the instructions need
only be skimmed.  Otherwise, read each step entirely and then perform
the action.  It is suggested that you place a check mark next to
each step as it is completed so that you won't skip anything.


\s+2Installing the 4P-ROM\s-2

.in .5i
.ti -.5i
1.	You will need a medium-sized Phillips screwdriver, a small
flat-blade screwdriver (1/4" wide tip or smaller), a large
towel (or towels) that will cover a 5' x 3' area, and a
table or workbench with at least 5' x 3' of space.

.ti -.5i
2.	Place the cloth or towel over the area that is to be used.
This will protect the surface of the table and the case of
computer during disassembly.

.ti -.5i
3.	Unplug the power cord and disconnect all other cables attached
to the computer.

.ti -.5i
4.	Remove the screen cover and set it aside.  

.ti -.5i
5.	Pull the keyboard out and place it on the right-hand side of
	the 4P.  Move it as far away as the cable will allow.

.ti -.5i
6.	Place the 4P face-down on the table so that the handle is on top.

7.	Remove the four white screws (two on either side) of the case.
These are painted screws, so be sure to use the proper-sized screwdriver
to avoid scraping the paint.

8.	Lift the handle and completely loosen (but don't remove) the two
screws that are located under the handle.  This is somewhat awkward to do,
but can be accomplished
by tilting the handle so that each screw can be accessed easier.  When
both screws are loose, remove the handle.  The screws will stay in
the handle-assembly unless you remove them.

9.	Open the cable access door, and remove the computer housing 
by lifting on the plastic housing with your fingers while pressing down on
the black metal plate with your thumb.  If the cover sticks, it may be
the warranty seal that is holding things down.  Break the seal and try again.

10.	Set the computer on its side, so that the screen is facing to
	your right and the floppy drives are on top.

11.	Remove the two unpainted phillips screws located between the
fan and the back plate.  (This area is behind the floppy drives, under the
cables for the floppy drives.)  The screws are holding a gold-colored
bracket in place.
Be careful not to drop the screws into the fan opening.

12.	Now lay the computer upside-down so that the back faces you. 
Remove the two unpainted phillips screws on the left end of the gold-colored
bracket.  Remove the bracket and set it aside.

13.	Along the sides of the case are eight screws, four on each side.
Remove three from each side, and loosen but do not remove the
two screws (one on each side) at the front.   One of the screws you remove
probably has a grounding cable attached to it.  This screw may be longer
than the others, so remember where it came from.

14.	Remove the three black screws along the top edge of the back of
the chassis.  These are located on either side of the data connectors.

15.	Gently pull the back metal plate (painted black) away and lift the
CPU pan (the surface facing up) so that the edge connectors are sticking
out above the back plate.

16.	Set the machine on its side so that the screen faces away from you
and the floppy drives are on top.  Remove the ribbon cable from the floppy
drives (not at the CPU board) so that the CPU pan can swing open wider.

17.	Swing open the CPU pan about six inches. 
Avoid opening the CPU pan wider than this, as it can cause some hard-to-reach
cables to become disconnected.

18.	Locate the existing boot ROM or EPROM.  Two different types of CPU
boards were built for the Model 4P, but the boot ROM is in the same place.
Look for a 24 pin part labelled U70 or U69, located roughly in the center
of the board. 

19.	If the ROM has small wires jumpered to it, don't worry.  Your
machine is an early model and the wires can be removed when the new
part is installed.  Although there may be two or three wires, only one
connects to the CPU board.  Cut that wire in half and place some tape
over the end so that it does not make contact with anything.  The other
wires do not require any action.

.ti -.5i
20.	On one end of the ROM, there will be a notch, indentation or small
"divot".  This indicates which end of the chip has pin 1.  It is
extremely important to remember which way the chip goes in so that
the new boot ROM can be installed correctly.   Although the CPU board
may also have a "1" marked on it indicating where pin 1 is, CPU
boards have been known to be incorrectly marked.  

.ti -.5i
15.	Remove the old ROM from the socket.
If you know how to remove the part, do so and skip to Step 16.   
If you have a SmartWatch installed, see the special instructions
at the end of this document.

If you don't know how to remove the chip, here is one way to do it
with the tools you have.   Using the blade of the flat-blade 
screwdriver, slip the end between the chip and the socket on either
end of the chip.  DO NOT try to do this between the pins.  Insert the
screwdriver only a quarter of an inch, or less.  Now rotate the
screwdriver VERY GENTLY so that the chip lifts away from the socket.
If you can't do this, then use the screwdriver as a lever and pry
the chip up NO MORE than 1/8 of an inch.  DO NOT try to pry the chip
out of its socket with a single motion or you could bend or break
the pins, or even crack the chip.

Now that you have one end of the chip lifted slightly, insert
the screwdriver further under the chip (about 3/4 of an inch, or
as far as it will go without forcing), and repeat the process.
This will lift the chip out of its socket without bending the pins.
You may have to insert the screwdriver one more time to completely
lift the chip.

If the chip has not fallen out, you should be able to grasp it on
each end with a finger and pull it straight out.  If it is too tight
to be removed using two fingers, repeat the screwdriver maneuver.

.ti -.5i
16.	Remove the new boot ROM from the foam or tube.  If the chip
was packaged in foam, check between the pins for any small pieces
of the foam that may have stuck to the pins or to the chip.
Remove these particles.

.ti -.5i
17.	Insert the old boot ROM into the foam or the tube.  This will
protect the part from static electricity.

.ti -.5i
18.	Insert the new boot ROM into the socket that the 
old part came from.  Make
sure the notch, indention or "divot" on the chip is facing the
same way as the part you removed.   This is most important, as 
improper insertion will ruin the boot ROM.

Line the chip up so that its legs are sitting in the sockets.
You may have to bend one or more pins ever so slightly to get them
all started into the socket.   When everything appears to be
lined up, press the chip into the socket part-way by pressing it
with your thumb.  Confirm that all the pins are still going into
the socket and that none are going outside the socket or are
bending under the chip.  (The top of the pin usually bows out
if the bottom of the pin is bending under the chip.)  A flashlight
or desk lamp is useful in checking this.  If one
or more pins are out of line, remove chip using the
screwdriver method, and straighten the pins out that are not
inserting properly.  Then try again.  It may take a few tries
to get all the pins going into the socket.

If the pins are still going into the socket after you have pushed
it halfway into place, push it down until it feels firmly seated.
There is usually about 1/8 to 1/16 of an inch between the bottom
of the chip and the socket when it is inserted properly.

Do not try to force the chip flush with the socket.  Some sockets
are designed to prevent you from doing this and the excessive
force could crack the CPU board.

Now run your finger along the pins on either side.  If a pin feels like
it is out of line, examine it carefully, as it may have folded under
the chip despite your efforts.  If you have a flashlight, examine
the pins by looking under the chip from one end.  If a leg is bent,
carefully remove the chip and straighten the leg by bending it very slowly
and try
again.  A chip leg can usually be straightened twice without breaking, 
but that is all.

.ti -.5i
19.	Close the CPU pan into its normal operating position
	and push the ribbon cable for the floppy drives back through the
	hole it goes through.


20.	Plug the floppy cable back into the two drives and make sure it and
the other wires in the area are not touching the fan.

21.	Install and tighten the three black screws in the back cover.


	Before the machine is assembled further, test the installation
	by following these steps.

22.	Turn the machine around so you can see the screen, but keep it
on end, with the floppy drives on top.  Make sure there are no floppies
in the disk drives.

23.	Plug the power cable into the jack on the back of the machine
and into a wall outlet.

24.	Turn the computer on.  After a few seconds, the light on floppy
drive 0 should come on and stay on for a few seconds.  Then the light
should go out and the message "The floppy disk drive is not ready"
should appear on the screen.  If this didn't happen to you, read the
following items and take the corrective action that is suggested.

A.	If no message appeared on the screen, adjust the brightness
and contrast to the maximum settings.  If you see random characters
on the screen, unplug the machine immediately.  The ROM is probably not
installed correctly.  Remove the three screws from the back, open
the CPU pan and check the ROM for improper insertion or bent pins.

B.	If the screen has a raster (the pattern of lines) but no
text, then the cable to the power supply or video section got disconnected
when the CPU pan was open.  This can happen when the pan is opened to wide.
Turn the power off and see the instructions for "Loose Video/Power/Reset
Cables"

C.	If the light on drive 1 came on instead of drive 0, the cable
going to the floppy drives is wired improperly.  Unplug the power and
plug the ribbon connector that was plugged into drive 1 into drive 0
and vice versa.

D.	If both floppy drive lights came on and stayed on, the ribbon
cable is plugged into the two drives upside down.  Unplug the
power cable and correct the cabling.  Then run this test again.

E.	If the neither drive light came on, and the message said
"The floppy disk drive is not available", the ribbon cable
to the floppy drives (or their power cables) are not connected.  Turn
the power off, check this out and try again.

25.	If that worked correctly, press the RESET button and then
press F1 within three seconds.  After a moment, you should see the
message "The hard disk drive is not available."  Again, if this didn't
work right, check the following items.

F.	If nothing happened when you pressed RESET (the screen did not
clear), the reset cable has probably come loose and must be reattached.
See the instructions for "Loose Video/Power/Reset Cables."

G.	If instead of an error message about the hard disk, you got an
error message about a floppy drive, the keyboard cable is probably loose.
Unplug the computer, seat the cable from the keyboard firmly into its
connector.  This can be done without opening the CPU pan by using the
side of a flathead screwdriver.

26.	If the above tests worked correctly, unplug the power cord
from the wall and the computer and proceed with the reassembly instructions.

27.	Turn the machine around so the front is away from you.
Reinstall the gold-colored bracket by installing the screws
next to the fan first and then install the screws on the other end.
These four screws hold the machine to the carrying-handle, so make sure
they are tight.

28.	Place the machine with the screen facing down, with the
keyboard on the left and the excess keyboard cable laying 
against the CPU pan.

29.	Install and tighten all eight screws (four per side) that are on
the sides of the CPU pan.  Remember to tighten the two at the front and
to reattach the grounding strap (if it was present.)

30.	Place the plastic housing over the chassis.  Make the housing is
oriented so that the data connectors are visible through the access
door.  Check the four holes that hold the white screws to ensure
that the case is lined-up properly.

31.	Install the handle so that the writing will be face-up when the
machine is in its up-right position.  Carefully tighten the two
screws that hold the handle in place.  Make sure these do not
get cross-threaded, and make sure they are tight.

32.	Install the four white screws.  

	This completes the installation procedure.


Loose Video/Power/Reset Cables


Near the front of the CPU pan are three rust-colored connectors that
connect the CPU to the reset switch, video monitor, and the power supply.
When the CPU pan is open, it is possible for one or more of these connectors
to become disconnected.

Depending on how much slack is available, you may be able to reach the loose
connector with you fingers or with needle-nose pliers, and reseat it on the
appropriate connector.

If you are unable to do this, remove the last two screws that hold the CPU
pan.  Once this is done, get all three connectors firmly back in position,
then close the pan and reinstall four or more screws.  Once you think you
have the pan back in operating position, go back and repeat the tests
that start at Step 22.


007021







.in 0
.ce

